(12749, 2, '2020-04-23 19:07:47', '2020-04-23 19:07:47', '‚I st Vietnamese adventure in the March of 2018., heading to Hanoi with a one-way ticket and $200 in his pocket. He has been volunteering on different projects and traveling around the country with the motorbike for the last 9 months and he’s going to share bits of the knowledge with you when it comes to volunteering in Vietnam. So, you’ve decided to volunteer in Vietnam? That’s awesome, but depending on your current country, it’s not a small step since you need to be ready for many sacrifices and a complete change in your lifestyle. Once you’ve got the idea of volunteering in a foreign country, don’t immediately rush to it, but let it stay for a while. Think about it and do the research constantly. If the idea still stays with you after a few months, then volunteering is probably a thing you should do. In this article, I’m going to write about the things you should know before deciding to volunteer in Vietnam. <b>Note: </b>Regulations and laws are constantly changing in Vietnam, so always be sure that you checked everything with your embassy before going to Vietnam. The last thing you want is to be deported from the country where you just wanted to help local community. Believe me, it can happen and it happened to many people before!\n\n<b>Questions to Ask Yourself Before Volunteering in Vietnam</b> Alright, so you started to think about volunteering in Vietnam, that’s great, but there are many questions that come to your mind probably. If that’s the case, then you’re in a good position since all of that is totally natural. <em>What are the reasons and motivations behind volunteering in Vietnam?</em> First of all, why do you want to travel to Vietnam and volunteer there? Is it a short-term to cut your traveling expenses or you really care about the community and believe you can help them with your skills? Think about it as if you go to Vietnam to volunteer without a purpose, you won’t feel satisfied and your time won’t help much. 2) What about logistics and costs of documentation and program. Please note that almost every program is free and some projects even pay a stipend for volunteers, so don’t pay extra for the program. What about your visa process? Does your volunteering organization support you in visa process and what kind of visa they provide?   3) Which organization you want to be a host of the project you’d like to work on. It’s a crucial question since there are so many organizations that are working just for the sake of money and you will basically help to bring more profits to these organizations. Be sure that you’re collaborating with NGOs who have every information transparent and who’re not putting the profits in their pockets, but really putting the money in the communities.   4) What kind of project you’d like to work on? The majority of projects in Vietnam is about English teaching, but there are many other projects. Be careful with English teaching projects since many project claim they help the poor and underdeveloped communities, but once you come you realize that you’re doing nothing else then putting the money inside the pockets of owners and helping privileged people, while poor still don’t have the access to English lessons. Choose carefully your project and be sure there are many reviews so you can connect with the people who were already working on the project.   5) How long do you plan to volunteer on the project in Vietnam? Well, if you’re planning to work with the kids as an English teacher, it’s important that you stay for longer periods, ideally 6 - 12 months since kids need to form the connection with teachers so they can get the most of the lessons. Also, you can do more harm than good if you’re working with the kids only for a short term.   6) Are your skills really necessary and are you taking the job opportunity from local people by working on a volunteering project? I really advise you to work on the project where your skills can make the difference since working on the other projects can take the job opportunity to a local person! That can do more harm than good!   7) How much money do you need for your stay and will you be able to budget your money correctly? What perks do you get from the organization in exchange for your time?   8) Does the organization offer the contract? Please be careful when reading the contract and always ask as many questions as possible!   Once you have the answers to these questions, I think you’re more than prepared to go over to Vietnam and start making a change.   I literally did an interview with the head of an organization, bought a one-way ticket and fly without any plan and just $200 in my pocket. There were tough times because I didn’t plan anything, but still, it teaches you how to be flexible and it’s not the hardest thing ever in Vietnam!   Don’t be like me and plan things accordingly!   <b>Where to Find a Volunteering Project That Really Makes a Difference?</b>   Once you’ve got all the answers for the questions above and you’ve decided to go to Vietnam to volunteer, it’s important that you find a suitable project for you.   Today, there are many places and platforms filled with volunteering projects, and it’s sometimes very tricky to know which platform or project is reliable. In this section, I will try to give you the guide on finding a reliable project that will really do the lasting impact on the local community.   Please note that I’m not a person with much experience! I’ve been volunteering only in Vietnam on different project related to English teaching and I’ve been using few platforms to find the projects. There are many other opportunities and ways to find a suitable project!   So, I advise you to check out three platforms (not an affiliate nor earning any money from the platforms. These I personally used and believe they are the most accurate):\n<ul>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Workaway which can be found at workaway.info</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Helpstay which can be found at helpstay.com</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Use different facebook groups for the fastest and most reliable communication with the hosts</li>\n</ul>\nI found my first project on the HelpStay platform when I was mindlessly scrolling around the platform and checking the projects in Vietnam. For the platform, you need to create an account which costs you $30 per year, but you can use the platform without the account. The account gives you the opportunity to outreach hosts and talk to them through the platform. I wrote a comprehensive review on HelpStay, so if you’d like to learn more about the platform, feel free to check it out.   I never subscribed to any platform not because I don’t support the platforms, but because I was totally broke at the time when I was looking for the project and $30 was a lot of money to me that time. The way I did was getting the information on the platform about the organization or host and then doing the further research on Google or Social media about the organizations. Usually, you will find the project and contact information in few minutes which is enough to get in contact with the right person.   The same goes with workaway! I don’t personally use workaway that much, but I’ve met hundreds of people who mainly use workaway for finding their next volunteering project.   I gave a try to workaway when I was traveling around Vietnam with a motorbike since I realized that majority of projects there are kind of short-term and people are using the platform to find a voluntourism opportunity. It works as a charm! It also has a subscription program where you need to get an account, but I’ve never got one. I just used the same strategy as I used for HelpStay.   Also, I wrote a huge review of Workaway, so if you’d like to know more about the platform, feel free to check it out.   In my perspective, Facebook groups are the best and fastest way to find your new volunteering project. The reason for it is that it’s free which means many people are using the platform and it’s transparent since the people posting the projects have the personal accounts they are using on a daily basis.   I suggest you to try these groups: - - - - -   Connect with hosts through Facebook, check their private profiles and organization profiles (website and social media). The best would be if you can get the information on previous or current volunteers so you can connect with them and talk about their experiences. That’s the thing you always want to do - talk with people who were working on the project!   Many organizations will post their projects and tell many good things while supporting a false marketing, but once you come there you will see how different the situation is! To avoid it, just talk with people who have the experience with the organization.   These are three ways I’ve been using when finding a volunteering project in Vietnam (or globally), but there are still other ways how to find a reliable project.   Probably there are crazy good ways to find the best project out there, and if you know it, don’t hesitate to share it with us!   <b>What to Expect From Volunteering in Vietnam?</b>   While volunteering in Vietnam, there are things you should expect to get in return for the time you invest.   The only thing you invest while you’re working on the project should be a time, but on many projects you will also need to invest your money. Also, don’t forget the time, energy and money you invested before coming to Vietnam! You should take all into the account when planning a new volunteering project.   So, when checking the volunteering opportunities in Vietnam, almost every project, which is connected to English teaching, will at least provide you with housing and some meals. Some projects even provide you with a stipend as they support foreigners to travel around Vietnam to experience the country after they finish the projects.   I was working on English teaching project in countryside where I’ve got everything covered; food, accommodation and transportation. It was a very cool experience, and here you can read about it in details.   I literally didn’t need to spend any money there, but in reality, I was spending around $80 per month, mainly on coffee and luxury meals. I was once broke without any money with me and I was living without a penny for 3 weeks. It was manageable, but not the biggest pleasure of my life.   Plan your budget accordingly depending on the place you’re planning to stay, so you avoid the situation when you run out of the money in a foreign country.   Probably you hear this a lot, but, don’t be like Antonio!   The second project I was working at was at cool English speaking cafe in Da Nang city. I stayed there for almost three months and had one of the best experiences of my life. I’ve met amazing people and had some of the best conversations with local people of my life. Also, I’ve learned so much about Vietnam staying at that place. They were offering a dorm room shared with 8 people, but without the meals. It was a fair deal since the food in Da Nang is quite cheap and you only work 4 times per week. It means a lot of free time to explore or work on the side, but you need to seriously plan your budget if you want to do it!   I was talking with some organizations and people who were volunteering for the organizations that claim they provide with stipend, usually $200 monthly, for their volunteers to cover the costs for traveling. Usually, the food and accommodation is paid by the host, but the real question comes when the money is involved.   How reliable it is?   Some people were lucky and they’ve got their money, while many people said there were lot of problems and time spent until they’ve got a portion or whole amount agreed. I personally wouldn’t put my cards on these stipends!   Always ask for a monthly pays and if they start to talk something different than agreed, just find another project!   Also, there are some NGO projects in remote areas that really make change on local community, but during the lack of funds, they ask volunteers for a small daily payments to support themselves.   <b>Actionable Steps to Find Your Next Volunteering Project in Vietnam!</b>   Enough information, let’s get to the real thing! Let’s get your first volunteering project in Vietnam.   Here are actionable steps that will help you in finding a meaningful project in Vietnam:\n<ol>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First things first, think about your reasons and motivation to go to Vietnam at first place. What kind of specific skills do you have and can you devote enough time to really make a difference?</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Register to Workaway or Helpstay or simply just use the platforms to scrape the information. If you don’t want to use any platforms, then Facebook groups will work more than fine. We shared many groups that will help you connect with amazing hosts and projects that make difference to local communities around the country.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Find a reliable project that has a transparent profile and positive reviews from other volunteers. Connect with the head of organization and talk about details of project. Also, don’t forget to connect with previous volunteers as these people will most-likely give you the genuine opinion based on their experience.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do the interview with the organization and confirm the documentation needed for you to legally volunteer for them. Legit volunteer organizations always sponsor their volunteers with the right visa which is usually a business visa. Vietnam always changes the policies when it comes to foreigners volunteering or working in Vietnam, so the safest would be to have a business visa. Check out what the organization offer you in return for the energy and time you invest into the project.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once you’re happy with the details and confident you’re going to volunteer for a certain project, it’s time to plan your budget depending on the perks of the project. Plan your budget carefully since you don’t want to run out of the money in Vietnam.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Buy a plane ticket and get ready for your next adventure!</li>\n</ol>\nThat’s it! Everything in 6 steps!   It’s not looking like a complicated process, but believe me you will probably spend at least a month just thinking and planning this adventure. There are so many opportunities and options which makes it very hard and tricky to pick the right one.   Don’t worry if you think it takes you much time, you’re not the only one!   Just relax, take your time and plan accordingly.   Wish you all the luck in your next adventure in Vietnam. Once you’re here, don’t forget to send us a message so we can connect and help each other!   Also, if you need a help while looking for a reliable project, I really advise to check out my experience volunteering as an English teacher in rural Vietnam. I can share with you the information and connect you with the right people who can help you to come and work on the same project.   Cheers!', 'All You Need to Know About Volunteering in Vietnam', 'TODO: Write Excerpt\r\n', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'all-you-need-to-know-about-volunteering-in-vietnam', '', '', '2020-04-23 19:18:29', '2020-04-23 19:18:29', '', 0, 'http://localhost/vietnam_chronicles/?p=12749', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(12750, 2, '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'On the Ha Giang loop, you will come in touch with many ethnic minority groups, as the Ha Giang Province is predominantly populated by such groups.  Travelers on the Ha Giang loop have an unique opportunity to see the daily lives of the Northern Vietnamese people. As you ride through their villages, you will see them wearing their fascinating and colorful traditional garments.  In most of their communities, you will see how each person in the community has a role to play. You will see women carrying their baskets in colorful clothes, children playing around and helping out their parents with their work and men hard at work with building new structures for the community.  Seeing these people working hard every day as a close-knit community and still managing to keep their smiles wide is incredibly astonishing. Especially for someone coming from the more individualistic, Western culture.  <em>Now, here is an overview of some of the most known ethnic groups in Ha Giang.</em> <h2><strong>Hmong People</strong></h2> The Hmong are the largest ethnic group out of 17 more in the Dong Van Karst Plateau Geo Park area. They migrated from China to Northern Vietnam 300 years ago. Now, the Hmong are mainly populating mountainous provinces such as Ha Giang.  Actually, the Hmong make up 32% of the total population of the Ha Giang province. They can be divided into two subgroups: <strong>White Hmong </strong>and <strong>Flower Hmong</strong>.  The Hmong are renowned for their traditional milpa - a type of a crop-growing system. In such a system, they plant rice, maize and other crops together.  They also produce handicrafts and are highly skilled in making wooden furniture, casting, forging, knitting and weaving.  How does a traditional Hmong house look like? It is mainly made from earth and is divided into three compartments. The middle compartment of the Hmong house is reserved as the altar for their ancestor cult.  You can recognize the Hmong women wearing unique traditional clothing. Their clothing style consists of a skirt, blouse, shirt, belt, leggings and a turban that is knitted around the head. Also, their dresses usually have decorative patterns such as butterflies, snakes, flowers, bird eyes and more to make them stand out.  The traditional customs, ceremonies, habits, and rituals are quite numerous in the Hmong groups. Each family has a different way of worshipping their ancestors. They also worship numerous spirits, some of them being the Door Ghost and the Great Mother Ghost, which are related to their ancestor worship and hospitality to the guests.  The Hmong literature and art show their psychological profile as a community. They have a lot of lovely traditional songs about love that they play using flute, pan-pipe, and leaf-horn. <h2><strong>Dao People</strong></h2> The Dao people can be divided into several sub-groups: <ul>          <li>Red Dao</li>          <li>Coin Dao</li>          <li>White Trousers Dao</li>          <li>Long Robe Dao</li>          <li>Lo River Dao</li> </ul> These people live off farming and they usually have their farms on mountain slopes where they make the rice terraces.  They possess unique handicraft skills such as casting, embroidery, forging, jewelry and wax-printing and dyeing clothes.  The Dao people live in stilt or earth houses, close to rivers and other water sources. You will usually see their houses made out of a combination of stilt and earth.  The Dao people can be spotted wearing dresses with traditional features and designs that are made from colored thread. They have lots of types of turbans, skirts, and shirts.  The Dao ethnic minority group follows a complex religion and culture. Their beliefs demonstrate communal spirit, conscience, and conception. Worship and wizardry isn\'t just a mere superstition to them. They look at these things as something special and that indicated the depth of their culture, no matter how hard it may be to understand for an outsider.  The Dao people have a rich folkloric literature that consists of numerous legends, myths, stories, and pop songs. All of that folklore implies their perception of how the universe and human life are communal, and that further establishes their communal spirit. <h2><strong>Tay People</strong></h2> This is the second-largest ethnic minority in the Ha Giang Province. The Tay people make up 25% of the total province population. They live off planting rice in wet fields near the rivers, mountain feet, and farming slopes.  The Tay build their villages at the mountain foot. The villages usually consist of 15 - 20 houses. Their houses are made of stilt while the roof is made of palm leaves or grass using the thatch method.  They have a developed family handicraft and are skilled in making wooden furniture, knitting and pottery. Their weaving craft is well-known around the region. They make blankets and brocade turbans, utilizing rich patterns that are adored by many people.  The Tay people can be recognized wearing cotton clothes that are indigo dyed with accessories such as silver necklaces and silver rings. Actually, the main color of their garments is indigo.  The Tay people have a very diversified culture. They have different kinds of ceremonies for food production, newborns, weddings and funerals. The Tay even celebrate the building of new houses!  They have rich folklore and literature too that consist of legends, myths, ancient stories, and folkloric songs. The Tay people practice Then religion. The main characteristics of this religion are ancestor worship and the worship of the gods of the natural environment. <h2><strong>Nung People</strong></h2> The Nung ethnic minority group can be mainly found in the Quan Ba district. They live in valleys located near the rivers, streams, and hills. These people live off farming rice and they utilize a high cultivation technique with rice terraces on mountain slopes. They also live off highly developed animal raising.  As with other ethnic minorities in Ha Giang, the Nung people possess handicraft skills that are very diverse. That included casting, carpentering, forging, knitting, and very diverse cloth weaving techniques.  Their clothing is mainly indigo colored. You can spot Nung women wearing robes of five panels with buttons under the right armpit. The Nung men wear shirts with an upright collar that leaves their breasts and bellies open.  They live in stilt houses that have two compartments. The outer compartment is reserved for men and ancestor worship, while the inner compartment is reserved for women. This indicates the roles of the genders in the Nung community.  The Nung people don\'t celebrate death anniversaries. They have colorful birthday celebrations and worship the dead on the 15th of July of the lunar calendar every year.  One tradition that stands out in the Nung community is the wedding ceremony. This ceremony preserves numerous ancient customs that the Nung stay true to. The brother of the bridegroom\'s mother plays an important role in this tradition. He represents the bridegroom family in the marriage proposal and organizes all the ceremonies that are related to the wedding.  Nung people also have rich folklore. Their folklore is famous for <em>Sli</em>, a love dialogue song of young people. <h2><strong>Giay People</strong></h2> The Giay ethnic minority group lives off rice and the milpa cultivation system. They organize the <em>Rong Pooc</em> ceremony every year to begin their farming season. The Giay build pig pens and hen coops in their fields, far from their houses.  These people are noteworthy for their handicrafts. They are highly skilled in bamboo knitting and weaving.  You can spot them wearing simple dresses, with no noteworthy design. The men wear a shirt with wide sleeves that is opened at the right armpit and wide trousers that are shortened to knee length. You can see women wearing a dress that consists of a robe that covers the buttock. This dress has broad sleeves and is opened at the right armpit. They also tend to put a different colored piece of clothing on the sleeves to stand out.  The Giay people live in stilt houses of 3 compartments. Middle compartment of the house is reserved for ancestor worship. The altar in the middle compartment has three bowls that are reserved for the Land God, the Kitchen God, and the ancestors.  They have interesting marriage customs too! When the youngsters attain a mature age for marriage, they don\'t choose their brides. Instead, their horoscope signs are taken into the notion and they are paired with suitable horoscope signs.  The Giay people also have rich folklore that consists of many poems, proverbs, and phrases. <h2><strong>Lo Lo People</strong></h2> We can divide the Lo Lo people into two sub-groups: <strong>Flower Lo Lo </strong>and <strong>Black Lo Lo</strong>. They have lived in Lung Cu area since the ancient times and they have made many efforts for their land to remain untouched.  The Lo Lo people have a very rich and unique folklore and culture that is preserved in their dances, songs, and legends.  Their turbans, shirts, skirts, and trousers are decorated with lots of colors.  The Lo Lo calendar divides a year in 11 months. Each month corresponds to an animal name, similar to the lunar calendar.  This ethnic minority group is notable for the ancient bronze drums, which are holy for them. The bronze drums are buried with the dead for protection and are occasionally dug out for use. These drums are kept by the head of each Lo Lo family. They are only used during funerals or festivals, the main reason is to maintain the rhythm for the dances.  Actually, the Lo Lo people are one of the few Vietnamese ethnic groups that still use bronze drums. Interestingly, we can connect this traditional instrument to the legend of <em>the Flood</em>. The legend tells a story of a climactic flood that raised the water levels up to the sky, drawing parallels to many other mythologies.  So, the bronze drums come into play in this legend in a scene where the God saves a girl and her younger brother by placing the girl in a big bronze drum and the boy in a small bronze drum. They survived on the mountains after the flood, and became a couple, essentially becoming a symbol for a rebirth of humankind.  This legend impacts the Lo Lo perception of Yin and Yang symbols and the concept of birth. The mentioned perception is still preserved in how the Lo Lo people play the bronze drums - the male and female drums are played at the same time.  The Lo Lo people have a very specific burial ritual. They hang the bronze drums on a stand that is located at the feet of the dead and the drums must face each other. The drummer stands between the drums and alternates between each drum with only one end of the drumstick. They believe that the souls of the dead can only find their way back to ancestors with the sound of bronze drums. <h2><strong>Pu Peo People</strong></h2> The Pu Peo people exclusively populate the Ha Giang province. In fact, there are only 705 people of this ethnic minority group living in Dong Van, Meo Vac and Bac Me areas (at least according to the data from 1999). With such a low population, the Pu Peo ranks 53rd of 54 in the Vietnamese community in terms of population.  The first record of the Pu Peo group can be accounted to <em>Kien Van Tieu Luc</em>, a book written in the middle of the 18th century. They are also mentioned in early 19th century documents under the names of <em>Penti</em>, <em>Pentilolo</em>, <em>Kaobeo</em>, and finally, <em>Pu Peo</em>.  The Pu Peo people live scattered in the mountain areas along the Chinese border. They differ from the Hmong people because they build their villages of flat ground in mountain areas. The Pu Peo people are usually found in Pho La, Sung Trang, and Phu Lung. These places are connected by the sub-tropical climate that is essential to the Pu Peo for growing rice and using the forests to earn for their living.  The Pu Peo people believe that the success and failure of each family and individual is directly connected to the position of their land and house. Because of that belief, they have a deeply religious house building process.  They follow strict religious procedures that are integrated into the selection of the land, selection the trees for pillars and selection of the building itself with the climax of the relocating ceremony. Interestingly, Pu Peo believe that all of these procedures must be fulfilled before dawn for good luck.  <em>They also worship their ancestors. More specifically, they worship three ancestor generations:</em> <ul>          <li>Parents (<em>Pe</em>)</li>          <li>Grandparents <em>(Te Ngan)</em></li>          <li>Great grandparents <em>(Te Gao)</em></li> </ul> For each of these three generations, the Pu Peo will put a jar (<em>loog ten</em>) on the altar inside the house. Offerings are made to ancestors on the first day in the new house and are put in these jars. In each jar, they put a chicken, a few small balls of cooked rice and more meat. They also believe that these offerings must be completed until dawn. After the ceremony and the offerings are done, the relatives and neighbors will come with a chicken, a bottle of wine and some money to wish good luck for their hosts.  The Pu Peo people use the Zhou dynasty calendar. This calendar consists of cycles or <em>khuop mai</em>, Each cycle equals 12 years. The year consists of 12 months, 29 or 30 days make a month and 12 hours will make a single day. This calendar is similar to the usual Vietnamese lunar calendar in a way that there is a leap year every three years.  The Pu Peo people <a href=\"http://vietnamchronicles.com/tet-holiday-vietnam\">celebrate Tet holiday</a> as other ethnic groups do too!', 'Learn About Ha Giang Ethnic Groups', 'TODO: Write Excerpt\r\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/vietnam_chronicles/?p=12750', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(12751, 2, '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'If you\'re planning to visit central Vietnam, more specifically Hue, Da Nang or Hoi An, you should definitely not skip iconic Hai Van pass. Almost every backpacker you\'ll meet will share stunning stories and photos of their Hai Van pass motorbike trip. Is it only a hype or a real thing?', 'Hai Van Pass by Motorbike - Epic Biker\'s Adventure', 'TODO: Write Excerpt\r\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/vietnam_chronicles/?p=12751', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(12752, 2, '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Vietnam is a well-known destination for many things, but traditional food and the number of choices simply stand out. I\'ve never met a person who didn\'t mention Vietnamese food while sharing the experiences from Vietnam which was more than enough for me to deeply explore a diversity of Vietnamese cuisine. As Da Nang is my home, I was blessed enough with the opportunity to drive around local places and markets and try a huge variety of street food.  I must be honest, some food was amazing, while some not so much (Trung Vit Lon I\'m talking about you!), but what always impresses me is the number of choices. Literally, everyone will find their favorite bowl or salad, no matter how picky you are.  After almost a year of living in Da Nang, my girlfriend and I decided to make a list of local specialties and drive around the city in order to try different delicacies. Our list consists of more than 35 local dishes, but for now, we only had a chance to taste 16. As I\'m currently not in Vietnam, you can expect the updates a bit later.  Anyway, keep reading as we\'re going to write about our favorite Da Nang street food &amp; where to find the best portion in the city.  <strong>#1- Mi Quang</strong>  Alright, probably there is not a single person who hasn\'t stumbled upon Mi Quang restaurant or tried one bowl of this iconic central Vietnamese dish. As you travel around Vietnam, you\'ll notice the food slightly changes, and Mi Quang in Da Nang is the same as Pho in Hanoi. Originating from Quang Nam province (Da Nang is a former capital), Mi Quang comes in different varieties following traditional recipes. Locals enjoy this tasty dish for breakfast or lunch, but it\'s not odd to see Mi Quang served on death anniversaries or even Tet holiday.  An iconic bowl of Mi Quang has many ingredients that combined give a mouthwatering taste. Wide cooked rice noodles served with just a pinch of delicious broth and a combination of fresh herbs and spices. You can find many versions of this dish as locals love to experiment with shrimps, chicken, fish or beef. You\'ll get a small basket filled with fresh herbs such as basil, cilantro, onion leaves, mint and lettuce to spice it up. I really love to add a bit of chili powder, a few drops of lime juice and a bit of fish sauce for extra taste.  Since I was living in An Thuong area, I\'ve found a tiny restaurant that was always full for a lunchtime. They were serving Mi Quang exclusively and it\'s easy to get hooked. Alternatively, we enjoyed a bowl of this dish at the Han market or Thanh Khe district. I\'ll leave down the address and details, so you can enjoy a delicious bowl yourself! :)  #2- Pho Bo/Ga  An iconic Pho is a Vietnamese traditional dish that got so popular around the world. In Da Nang, Pho isn\'t such a thing (it\'s a dish from the north), but you can still find it in many places. I personally find Pho in Da Nang very delicious, but not something I\'d eat more than once in a week. On the other hand, Hanoi\'s Pho is definitely something I\'m eating every day. Like people always say about the soups - the broth is everything, so I guess Hanoians know their broth.  Probably everyone knows about Pho, so I don\'t want to go too deep about the ingredients and way of cooking. There are many versions of Pho, but the most common is with beef or chicken. A traditional Vietnamese soup has a delicious broth mixed with meat, fresh vegetables and herbs, and rice noodles. As I\'m really enjoying reading about Vietnamese history, the interesting fact about Pho becoming so popular around the world is that refugees from the world introduced this dish all around the world.  You can eat Pho around Da Nang in many places, and for me, it was kinda hard to find a Pho that can compare with Hanoi\'s version. Since my girlfriend knows good restaurants, we ended up on the other side of the Han river, sitting in a huge restaurant flocked by Korean tourists. She was swearing it\'s the best Pho in Da Nang. I liked it, but for me, it\'s simply not the food I prefer eating in Da Nang.  For Pho addicts (I know there are many here! :P ), you can find more details below:  &nbsp;  #3- Bun Thit Nuong + Nem Lui  &nbsp;  #4- Banh Mi  &nbsp;  #5- Banh Xeo  &nbsp;  #6- Trung Vit Lon  &nbsp;  #7- Mango Salad (Gia Xoi something)  &nbsp;  #8- Com Ga Quay  &nbsp;  #9- Banh Canh  &nbsp;  #10- Com Binh Dan  &nbsp;  #11- Che - photo needed  &nbsp;  #12- Kem Bo  &nbsp;  #13- Hu Tieu  &nbsp;  #14- Bun Hen (baby clams)  &nbsp;  #15- Banh Tieu  &nbsp;  #16- Banh Cuon  &nbsp;', 'Explore Da Nang Street Food Scene With Us', 'TODO: Write Excerpt\r\n', 'draft', 'open', 'open', '', '', '', '', '2019-11-30 00:00:00', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', '', 0, 'http://localhost/vietnam_chronicles/?p=12752', 0, 'post', '', 0);
