on English teaching project in countryside where I’ve got everything covered; food, accommodation and transportation. It was a very cool experience, and here you can read about it in details.   I literally didn’t need to spend any money there, but in reality, I was spending around $80 per month, mainly on coffee and luxury meals. I was once broke without any money with me and I was living without a penny for 3 weeks. It was manageable, but not the biggest pleasure of my life.   Plan your budget accordingly depending on the place you’re planning to stay, so you avoid the situation when you run out of the money in a foreign country.   Probably you hear this a lot, but, don’t be like Antonio!   The second project I was working at was at cool English speaking cafe in Da Nang city. I stayed there for almost three months and had one of the best experiences of my life. I’ve met amazing people and had some of the best conversations with local people of my life. Also, I’ve learned so much about Vietnam staying at that place. They were offering a dorm room shared with 8 people, but without the meals. It was a fair deal since the food in Da Nang is quite cheap and you only work 4 times per week. It means a lot of free time to explore or work on the side, but you need to seriously plan your budget if you want to do it!   I was talking with some organizations and people who were volunteering for the organizations that claim they provide with stipend, usually $200 monthly, for their volunteers to cover the costs for traveling. Usually, the food and accommodation is paid by the host, but the real question comes when the money is involved.   How reliable it is?   Some people were lucky and they’ve got their money, while many people said there were lot of problems and time spent until they’ve got a portion or whole amount agreed. I personally wouldn’t put my cards on these stipends!   Always ask for a monthly pays and if they start to talk something different than agreed, just find another project!   Also, there are some NGO projects in remote areas that really make change on local community, but during the lack of funds, they ask volunteers for a small daily payments to support themselves.   <b>Actionable Steps to Find Your Next Volunteering Project in Vietnam!</b>   Enough information, let’s get to the real thing! Let’s get your first volunteering project in Vietnam.   Here are actionable steps that will help you in finding a meaningful project in Vietnam:\n<ol>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First things first, think about your reasons and motivation to go to Vietnam at first place. What kind of specific skills do you have and can you devote enough time to really make a difference?</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Register to Workaway or Helpstay or simply just use the platforms to scrape the information. If you don’t want to use any platforms, then Facebook groups will work more than fine. We shared many groups that will help you connect with amazing hosts and projects that make difference to local communities around the country.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Find a reliable project that has a transparent profile and positive reviews from other volunteers. Connect with the head of organization and talk about details of project. Also, don’t forget to connect with previous volunteers as these people will most-likely give you the genuine opinion based on their experience.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do the interview with the organization and confirm the documentation needed for you to legally volunteer for them. Legit volunteer organizations always sponsor their volunteers with the right visa which is usually a business visa. Vietnam always changes the policies when it comes to foreigners volunteering or working in Vietnam, so the safest would be to have a business visa. Check out what the organization offer you in return for the energy and time you invest into the project.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once you’re happy with the details and confident you’re going to volunteer for a certain project, it’s time to plan your budget depending on the perks of the project. Plan your budget carefully since you don’t want to run out of the money in Vietnam.</li>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Buy a plane ticket and get ready for your next adventure!</li>\n</ol>\nThat’s it! Everything in 6 steps!   It’s not looking like a complicated process, but believe me you will probably spend at least a month just thinking and planning this adventure. There are so many opportunities and options which makes it very hard and tricky to pick the right one.   Don’t worry if you think it takes you much time, you’re not the only one!   Just relax, take your time and plan accordingly.   Wish you all the luck in your next adventure in Vietnam. Once you’re here, don’t forget to send us a message so we can connect and help each other!   Also, if you need a help while looking for a reliable project, I really advise to check out my experience volunteering as an English teacher in rural Vietnam. I can share with you the information and connect you with the right people who can help you to come and work on the same project.   Cheers!', 'All You Need to Know About Volunteering in Vietnam', 'TODO: Write Excerpt\r\n', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '12749-revision-v1', '', '', '2020-04-23 19:09:25', '2020-04-23 19:09:25', '', 12749, 'http://localhost/vietnam_chronicles/2020/04/23/12749-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
