e won’t help much. 2) What about logistics and costs of documentation and program. Please note that almost every program is free and some projects even pay a stipend for volunteers, so don’t pay extra for the program. What about your visa process? Does your volunteering organization support you in visa process and what kind of visa they provide?   3) Which organization you want to be a host of the project you’d like to work on. It’s a crucial question since there are so many organizations that are working just for the sake of money and you will basically help to bring more profits to these organizations. Be sure that you’re collaborating with NGOs who have every information transparent and who’re not putting the profits in their pockets, but really putting the money in the communities.   4) What kind of project you’d like to work on? The majority of projects in Vietnam is about English teaching, but there are many other projects. Be careful with English teaching projects since many project claim they help the poor and underdeveloped communities, but once you come you realize that you’re doing nothing else then putting the money inside the pockets of owners and helping privileged people, while poor still don’t have the access to English lessons. Choose carefully your project and be sure there are many reviews so you can connect with the people who were already working on the project.   5) How long do you plan to volunteer on the project in Vietnam? Well, if you’re planning to work with the kids as an English teacher, it’s important that you stay for longer periods, ideally 6 - 12 months since kids need to form the connection with teachers so they can get the most of the lessons. Also, you can do more harm than good if you’re working with the kids only for a short term.   6) Are your skills really necessary and are you taking the job opportunity from local people by working on a volunteering project? I really advise you to work on the project where your skills can make the difference since working on the other projects can take the job opportunity to a local person! That can do more harm than good!   7) How much money do you need for your stay and will you be able to budget your money correctly? What perks do you get from the organization in exchange for your time?   8) Does the organization offer the contract? Please be careful when reading the contract and always ask as many questions as possible!   Once you have the answers to these questions, I think you’re more than prepared to go over to Vietnam and start making a change.   I literally did an interview with the head of an organization, bought a one-way ticket and fly without any plan and just $200 in my pocket. There were tough times because I didn’t plan anything, but still, it teaches you how to be flexible and it’s not the hardest thing ever in Vietnam!   Don’t be like me and plan things accordingly!   <b>Where to Find a Volunteering Project That Really Makes a Difference?</b>   Once you’ve got all the answers for the questions above and you’ve decided to go to Vietnam to volunteer, it’s important that you find a suitable project for you.   Today, there are many places and platforms filled with volunteering projects, and it’s sometimes very tricky to know which platform or project is reliable. In this section, I will try to give you the guide on finding a reliable project that will really do the lasting impact on the local community.   Please note that I’m not a person with much experience! I’ve been volunteering only in Vietnam on different project related to English teaching and I’ve been using few platforms to find the projects. There are many other opportunities and ways to find a suitable project!   So, I advise you to check out three platforms (not an affiliate nor earning any money from the platforms. These I personally used and believe they are the most accurate):\n<ul>\n 	<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Workaway which can be found at workaway.info</li>\n 	<li s